


The GO function-like macro "go.h"

            The GO function-like macro has the effect that
                -   an int object is declared in the scope where
                    the macro invocation appears,
                -   the function specified by #1 is called with
                    the arguments specified by any arguments
                    specified after #1 then,
                -   the return value of the call is assigned to
                    the variable specified by #0.
                -   If the call returns a positive value, an
                    error message is sent to the standard error
                    stream and the function containing the macro
                    invocation returns 1. Otherwise,
                -   if the call returned zero, the value of the
                    variable specified by #0 is set to 0, and
                    execution continues. Otherwise,
                -   the call returned an negative value, the
                    value of the variable specified by #0 is set
                    to -1, and execution continues.

    Example
    
            The n function always returns -1. The z function
            always returns 0. And the p function always
            returns 1.

            int zero ( void ) { return  0 ; }

            int pos  ( void ) { return +9 ; }

            int neg  ( void ) { return -9 ; }

            int n ( void )
            {
                GO ( y , neg ) ;
                return y ;
            }

            int z  ( void )
            {
                GO ( y , zero ) ;
                return y ;
            }

            int p ( void )
            {
                GO ( y , one ) ;
            }
